'''Takiyettin Mengusoglu''' (1905–1984) was a Turkish philosopher.<ref>http://felsefe.istanbul.edu.tr/node/52</ref>
Mengusoglu was born in Malatya province of Turkey. After finishing the high school he went to Germany and became a student of [[Nicolai Hartmann]]. He was known as Takiyettin Temuralp at that time and published '''Über die grenzen der erkennbarkeit bei Husserl und Scheler''' in German.<ref>[http://www.husserl.net/books/title.php?opt=3&source=793]</ref> He is the author of the university textbook '''Felsefeye Giris (Introduction to Philosophy)'''.<ref>http://www.remzi.com.tr/index.asp?anakategori=59&kategori=149&kitapid=933</ref>
Mengüşoğlu founded a new school of [[anthropology]] which he called ontological anthropology. This anthropology deals with man not through any conceptualization but through "his concrete biopsyhichic wholeness".<ref>http://www.edebiyatdergisi.hacettepe.edu.tr/2000172SevgiIyi.pdf</ref><ref>Iyi, Sevgi, "Yüzyılımızda İki Antropoloji Anlayışı, [[Heidegger]] ve Mengüşoğlu", ''Hacettepe Üniversitesi Edebiyat Fakültesi Dergisi'', 17(2):1</ref> He believed that this new anthropology would be more suitable approaching man and solving concrete problems in the human world.
